{"title_page": "Sailana State", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=July 2017}}\n{{Infobox former subdivision\n|conventional_long_name = Sailana State\n|common_name = Sailana\n|nation = [[British India]]\n|status_text = [[Princely State]]\n|era = \n|year_start = 1736\n|date_start = \n|event_start= \n|year_end = 1948\n|date_end = \n|event_end= accession to the Indian Union\n|event1 = \n|date_event1 = \n|p1 =\n|s1 = India\n|flag_p1 = \n|flag_s1 = Flag of India.svg\n|image_flag =Sailanaflag.png\n|image_coat = Sailana State CoA.png\n|image_map = \n|image_map_caption =\n|stat_area1 =769\n|stat_year1 =1881\n|stat_pop1 = 29,723\n|footnotes = [http://www.indianrajputs.com/view/sailana Sailana (Princely State)]\n}}\n'''Sailana State''' was an 11 gun salute [[princely state]] in India, part of the [[Malwa Agency]] of [[Central India Agency|Central India]] during the [[British Raj]]. The state enjoyed an estimated revenue of [[Pound sterling|\u00a3]]40,360 in 1881.<ref>[https://books.google.co.in/books?id=7JQbAQAAIAAJ&pg=PA142&dq=imperial+gazetteer+sailana+state&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjmibm534flAhU-H7cAHXpYDp8Q6AEIKDAA#v=onepage&q=imperial%20gazetteer%20sailana%20state&f=true The Imperial Gazetteer of India, Volume 12, pg 141]</ref>\n\n==History==\nSailana State was founded by Raja Jai Singh, great-grandson of Maharaja Ratan Singh, founder of [[Ratlam State]]. In 1716 Jai singh took revenge against his uncle for the murder of his father, he killed him in a pitched battle at sagode and secured [[Ratlam]] for his elder brother. The two brothers then divided the state between themselves. Jai singh's capital was initially at [[Raoti]]. He built [[Sailana]] town as his new capital in 1736. He fought 22 battles in his lifetime, turning Sailana into an independent state.<ref>Malwa in Transition Or a Century of Anarchy: The First Phase, 1698\u20131765 pg.123\u2013125</ref><ref name=\"igi\">{{cite book|url=https://archive.org/stream/imperialgazettee015643mbp#page/n391/mode/2up|title=Imperial Gazetteer of India|volume=Vol.21|year=1908|publisher=Clarendon Press|location=Oxford|pages=385\u20137}}</ref> During Raja Mokham Singh's rule, [[Sailana]] suffered in war against the [[Scindia]]s of [[Gwalior]], most of the states eastern and southern lands were annexed. Raja Lakshman Singh of [[Sailana]] tried to push the Scindia's out of his kingdom, in 1818 he refused to pay [[chauth]] which was regularly levied, the Scindias retaliated by sending an army under Bujang Rao, the [[Gwalior]] army which had European arms and was French trained lost its advantage on the hills en route to [[Sailana]] and was defeated by Lakshman Singh, the captured soldiers were allowed to leave but all of their guns and artillery were taken. In 1819, Bapu Rao was appointed to punish the raja of [[Sailana]] and enforce tribute upon him. Bapu Rao had previously been sent by the Scindia's to defeat and exact tributes from the Maharaja of [[Jaipur]] and the Maharana of [[Udaipur]].<ref>History of the Marathas By R.S. Chaurasia p.41</ref> However on 5 January 1819, [[John Malcolm]] mediated between [[Gwalior]] and [[Sailana]] upon which Raja Lakshman Singh accepted British protection and agreed to pay a fixed tribute of \u00a34,200 to [[Gwalior]] (until 1860),<ref>https://books.google.co.in/books?id=7JQbAQAAIAAJ&pg=PA142&dq=imperial+gazetteer+sailana+state&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjmibm534flAhU-H7cAHXpYDp8Q6AEIKDAA#v=onepage&q=imperial%20gazetteer%20sailana%20state&f=false</ref> in return for [[Scindia]] agreeing to refrain from any interference in [[Sailana]]. During British rule [[Sailana]] saw development under the capable rule of Raja [[Jashwant Singh II]] and then under his son Raja [[Dileep Singh]], many reforms were introduced over the coming years, with particular attention being paid to education and the provision of vernacular educational facilities. By 1947, education and medical aid were provided free of charge, the local municipality was placed on a democratic footing and the judiciary and executive made independent of each other. Although the economy was primarily agricultural, some limited industrialisation included oil mills, and iron and steel works. On 15 June 1948, Raja [[Dileep Singh]] signed the accession to the [[Dominion of India|Indian Union]].<ref>[http://www.worldstatesmen.org/India_princes_K-W.html#Shailana Princely States of India]</ref><ref>Sailana through the ages by Jayantilaal Mehta</ref>\n\n==Rulers==\nThe chiefs of Sailana are [[Rathore]] [[Rajput]]s and have a common ancestry with the Maharajas of [[Jodhpur State|Jodhpur]] and [[Ratlam State|Ratlam]].<ref>[https://books.google.co.in/books?id=47sfj8DUwNgC&pg=PA629&dq=sailana+state&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjH5ZyivLjoAhW3yDgGHaD2A3UQ6AEIKjAB#v=onepage&q&f=true Indian States: A Biographical, Historical, and Administrative Survey By R. V. Solomon, J. W. Bond. Pg.629]</ref>\n\n===Rajas=== \n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Name !! Year\n|-\n| Jai Singh || 1736\u20131757\n|-\n| Jaswant Singh || 1757\u20131772\n|-\n| Ajab Singh || 1772\u20131782\n|-\n| Mokham Singh || 1782\u20131797\n|-\n| Lakshman Singh|| 1797\u20131826\n|-\n| Ratan Singh || 1826\u20131827\n|-\n| Nahar Singh || 1827\u20131841\n|-\n| Takhat Singh || 1841\u20131850\n|-\n| Rajmata Nath Kanwarji (regent) || 1850\u20131859\n|-\n| Duleh Singh || 1850\u20131895\n|-\n| [[Jashwant Singh II]] || 1895\u20131919\n|-\n| [[Dileep Singh]] || 1919 \u2013 1948 (1948 \u2013 1961 titular)\n|-\n| Digvijay Singh (titular) || 1961\u20131990\n|-\n| Vikram Singh (titular) || 1990 \u2013 present\n|}\n\n==Jagirdars of Sailana State==\n\nAll the jagirdars owe fealty and service to the ruler and pay cesses and tanka. No jagirdar has the right to adopt without the permission of the raja. The 1st class jagirdars are allowed to wear gold anklets, and at their succession, they are installed by the ruling raja himself. Half of the states lands were alienated because of the large number of Jagirs.<ref name=\"igi\"/> Raja Dilip Singh ({{reign|1919|1948}}) later extinguished several Jagirs and replaced them with governors. This harsh but effective action helped the states revenue which was then used to provide medical and educational facilities in Sailana.<ref>Rulers, Leading families, and officials in the states of central India Pg.152\u2013154</ref><ref>Sailana through the ages by Jayantilaal Mehta p. 109</ref>\n\nThe following were the 1st class Jagirdars of Sailana in 1908.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Name !! Revenue (Rs.) !! Dynasty\n|-\n| Semlia || 30,000 || Rathore\n|-\n| Birmawal/Kaneri || 26,000 || Rathore\n|-\n| Raoti || 20,000 || Rathore\n|-\n| Kariya || 17,000 || Rathore\n|-\n|}\n\nThe following were the 2nd class Jagirdars of Sailana in 1908.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Name !! Revenue (Rs.) !! Dynasty\n|-\n| Ghatwas || 5,00 || Rathore\n|-\n| Umran || 4,000 || Songara\n|-\n| Nayapura || 1,100 || Rathore\n|-\n| Mewasa || 3,000 || Sisodia\n|-\n| Chandoria || 2,000 || Rathore\n|-\n| Nalkui || 1,700 || Songara\n|-\n| Kotria || 1,200 || Rathore\n|-\n| Bharoda || 4,000 || Rathore\n|-\n| Advania || 6,000 || Rathore\n|-\n| Morda || 4,000 || Rathore\n|-\n|}\n\nThe 3rd class jagirdars were hereditary office holders of the state.\n\n==Coins of Sailana==\n[[File:Sailana.jpg|thumb|One-quarter anna coins of Sailana state, minted in 1908 and 1912.]]\nThe original currency of Sailana was the \"Salim Shahi\". They were copper coins which were minted in Sailana State. However after 1897 Salim Shahi was discontinued and replaced with the British Rupee.<ref name=\"igi\"/> Sailana was under British protection, and issued coins of same design as British India coinage, minted by the same mints. One-quarter anna (1 paisa) coins of Sailana were minted in 2 years \u2013 1908 and 1912 \u2013 these coins were the same size, weight and composition as the British India one-quarter anna coin. On one side, these coins had the portrait of the Emperor, Edward VII in 1908 and George V in 1912. The reverse of the coin mentioned the name of the Sailana state.<ref>https://www.tezbid.com/blogs/blogs/p-know-your-india-coins-of-sailana-p-p-p</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of Rajput dynasties and states]]\n*[[Malwa Agency]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.uq.net.au/~zzhsoszy/ips/s/sailana.html Sailana princely state]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110505082217/http://www.royalhouseofsailana.com/index.html Royal house of Sailana]\n\n{{MP Princely States}}\n{{Princely states of India}}\n\n{{Coord|23.47|N|74.92|E|region:IN-GU_type:city_source:kolossus-cawiki|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Princely states of Madhya Pradesh]]\n[[Category:Ratlam district]]\n[[Category:Rajputs]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2017}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=July 2017}}\n{{Infobox former subdivision\n|conventional_long_name = Sailana State\n|common_name = Sailana\n|nation = [[British India]]\n|status_text = [[Princely State]]\n|era = \n|year_start = 1736\n|date_start = \n|event_start= \n|year_end = 1948\n|date_end = \n|event_end= accession to the Indian Union\n|event1 = \n|date_event1 = \n|p1 =\n|s1 = India\n|flag_p1 = \n|flag_s1 = Flag of India.svg\n|image_flag =Sailanaflag.png\n|image_coat = Sailana State CoA.png\n|image_map = \n|image_map_caption =\n|stat_area1 =769\n|stat_year1 =1881\n|stat_pop1 = 29,723\n|footnotes = [http://www.indianrajputs.com/view/sailana Sailana (Princely State)]\n}}\n'''Sailana State''' was an 11 gun salute [[princely state]] in India, part of the [[Malwa Agency]] of [[Central India Agency|Central India]] during the [[British Raj]]. The state enjoyed an estimated revenue of [[Pound sterling|\u00a3]]40,360 in 1881.<ref>[https://books.google.co.in/books?id=7JQbAQAAIAAJ&pg=PA142&dq=imperial+gazetteer+sailana+state&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjmibm534flAhU-H7cAHXpYDp8Q6AEIKDAA#v=onepage&q=imperial%20gazetteer%20sailana%20state&f=true The Imperial Gazetteer of India, Volume 12, pg 141]</ref>\n\n==History